Provincial traffic chief Kenny Africa said  six crashes had been reported since Friday. In one crash a three-year-old child and the driver died on Christmas Day when a taxi ploughed into stationary vehicles in Grabouw. A 27-year-old pedestrian was knocked down and killed on the N1 near De Doorns, and another pedestrian died on the R43 near Hermanus yesterday. ER24â€™s Russel Meiring said paramedics, along with other emergency services, arrived 
on the scene to find the body of a man lying in the middle of the road on the N1 near De Doorns. The car that hit him was found parked 200m away. Paramedics assessed the man and found that he had sustained multiple injuries. He was declared dead at the scene, Meiring said. Along the Klipheuwel/ Stellenbosch road a driver died after losing control of this car yesterday. Along the same road on Christmas Day, a traffic officer was hit by an unlicensed driver, who was arrested for drunken driving. The officer is still in hospital with serious injuries. Africa said on Friday in Worcester a car veered out of control and the driver and two passengers were killed In Beaufort West a passenger died after a head-on collision between two taxis. - Staff Writer